metadata.name: sketch: cairn() #41
metadata.description:
A cairn is a monument made of stacked rocks. In modern times, often used for wayfinding in remote areas, as in mountaineering, or to indicate an area of significance.

In this sketch I imagine these monuments -- through the looking glass. Paying mind to the simplicity of their construction, as well as the mysticism of what each might represent.

---

Sketch is a series meant to celebrate learning and experimentation.

In this sketch I experiment with subdivision, smoothing, textures, multiple levels of domain warping, and illustration techniques.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press s to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at size

metadata.name: All Fold: Sketch #291
metadata.description:
'All Fold: Sketch' is a generative system intended to celebrate the writing and artwork that can only be found in the pages of a sketchbook. The project itself is much like a sketch, and attempts to represent the spirit of a work-in-progress.

The fold is included as a reminder that there is always another page.

In the context of the market, the pricing of this project is intended to offer an enjoyable minting experience, while giving the opportunity to contribute to important charities.

- 60% of any primary sales will be split between "Girls Who Code" and "Cure Parkinson's"
- 60% of any royalties will be split between "Girls Who Code" and "Cure Parkinson's"

The aesthetics of this project were directly inspired by the works of Gunta St√∂lzl, Anni Albers, Gertrud Arndt, Kenneth Martin, and Josef Albers.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2023.

metadata.name: Isola della Scala #74
metadata.description:
All things pass, all things flow,
Movement, connection, separation, all in tow.
A misstep and we're knocked off course,
But in the end, we rise, as if by force.
Like a dance of dominoes, we fall and we stand,
In this ever-changing world, we're a part of the grand.

The name of this work is the name of the city where my roots began, where the path of everything changed and new directions in life were taken.

Made with p5.js, p5.grain and much love

metadata.name: Antigravity #432
metadata.description:
To change size or quality, open the IPFS link in a separate window and append to its url a string like `&quality=400&tiles=9,16`. You may notice two parameters in it: `quality` and `tiles`.

`quality` is an integer from 1 to ~1000, the better the quality ‚Äî the slower the rendering. Default is 200.

`tiles` is a number of 256√ó256 px tiles to render. Can be an integer (for square images) or two integers separated with a¬†comma (for rectangular). `tiles=9,16` will make an image with width of 9√ó256 px = 2304 px and height of 16√ó256 px = 4096 px. If not set, adapts to screen size.

Press `s` to save the image.

metadata.name: Tendencies #35
metadata.description:
Tendencies is the first in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art in the 1970s.

Zajec's generative work was motivated by redundancy in his paintings: "The monotony of the manual task and the limited number of variations which I was able to produce in a given time made me realize the inadequacy of traditional methods in dealing with our present reality." Tendencies was inspired by ‚Äî and pays tribute to ‚Äî one if Zajec's earliest forays into generative creation: a work titled RAM 10 V.15, which was written on an IBM 1620 and programmed in FORTRAN.

The title of the collection itself is a reference to the first exhibition of Zajec's RAM series, while the number of editions minted referencing the year Zajec put plotter to paper.

Made in p5js
Created December 2022
By @christine_hall

metadata.name: Holy Mountain #101
metadata.description:
Mountains throughout human history have taken on deep meanings. Coated with immense sacredness by all peoples in the most different places. Being them as a representation of God himself or being the object of worship. For many the mountains were the very abode of the Gods. They are in the collective unconscious as the ability to connect men and gods, through the flow of energy between earth and heaven.

The symbology is very strong. It unconsciously reminds us of the process of encounter between the loneliness of the earth and the hope of the sky, between the fog that blinds and the cloud that supports, between the abyss of the ground and the proximity of the stars. All this is very charming and fascinating.

All human beings have their own mountain, which demands from each one their limits to reach the top, the desire for the breathtaking view, the fear of falling, but also the hope of the last step at the highest point.

In generative art it couldn't be different, going through all the learning, from its fundamentals, to all the countless hours of tests, to countless moments of problem solving and research and more research. This whole process is without a doubt like climbing a mountain. Thinking about the project is exactly like looking at a mountain and imagining how exhausting it will be all the way to conquer it. Finishing your work is like breathing a sigh of relief, looking down and seeing how hard it was to get there, but at the same time looking ahead and realizing how rewarding it was to be able to have that vision and breathe the refreshing breeze of the moment.

After going through a transformation in my first work, where I transmuted my artistic essence from illustration to generative art. Now I come to this second work that I delved into, and after months of climbing this mountain of mine, I give it to you.


- Press "S" in live view mode after loading to save at 1600x1600px.

metadata.name: Lucky Oracles #264
metadata.description:
"Lucky Oracles" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

Eko33, is a Swiss-French generative artist who has been at the forefront of digital arts since 1999 when he started writing code to create generative artworks and installations. He made his debut using a Commodore SX-64 and floppy disks. Since then, his work has been exhibited in Museums, International art fairs, and biennales. His work is focused on nonfigurative, generative art while using custom algorithms and innovative technology.

metadata.name: Cyanotypes #275
metadata.description:
This is an algorithmic tribute to the pioneering work of Anna Atkins (1799-1871). Considered by many the first female photographer, Atkins learned about the cyanotype process soon after it was invented by John Herschel, a family friend. As a botanist, she had the idea of using the new technique to produce contact prints of plants. Her investigations succeeded in capturing the nuances in morphology and the delicate details of many species.

In 1843 she published ‚ÄúBritish Algae: Cyanotype impressions‚Äù, the first published book to use a photographic process for the illustrations. Each copy gathered around 400 prints, each of them individually produced from a different specimen. Thus, all books featured the same species, but each of them was different, in a process that was itself generative in a certain way. Today, about 17 copies of the book are preserved in different institutions. Atkins went on to publish two more books in the following years, with the help of her friend Anne Dixon, dedicated to various ferns and plants.

‚ÄúCyanotypes‚Äù pays homage to her wonderful work, which sits at the intersection between science and art, and used technology in a novel way to capture the beauty of nature. Here things are taken one step forward, to generate algorithmic simulations of plants, ferns, and algae, which are the work of fantasy and not necessarily faithful to the traits of any real species.

The work features 28 basic configurations, each of them in turn capable of unlimited variations. As was the case with the prints from ‚ÄúBritish Algae‚Äù, every image is at the same time part of a series and unique. 

Controls:
[SPACE] to play/pause
[r] to restart the drawing
[f] to toggle fullscreen
[s] to download capture
[2] to [9] to generate and save a hi-res image at multiples of the original 800 x 1000 resolution. Please note that rendering at high resolutions can be very slow.

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: GuilCity #109
metadata.description:
GuilCity is the beginning of an exciting journey bringing Guillaume Cornet‚Äôs densely-packed cities into the generative realm with the help of Matthew‚Äôs (@frostbitten‚Äôs) magic touch.

Matthew‚Äîwith his background in coding and animation‚Äîenables a new opportunity to experience these cities like never before. Numerous elements from vehicles to characters and even architecture have been given life. Interact with the city (computer mouse only): poke and peek around (even behind) in this active search & find journey! 

Each generative city fills the composition with the type of whimsical, expressive elements and characters you‚Äôve come to know Guil for. What kinds of wacky features have you discovered yet?

‚Äî

The tech behind this project utilizes the highly compressed WEBP image format in order to provide so many full-color options. This format is great, but unfortunately Safari on desktop/laptop must be upgraded to at least version 14 and macOS to at least version 11 Big Sur to use it.

The animation system for this project was created from scratch with additional help from the PIXI.js library for individual mesh animations.

‚Äî

To find out more about your GuilCity, copy your unique operation hash and place it at the end of the following url:
‚Ä¢ https://my.guil.city?fxhash=
(for example: https://my.guil.city?fxhash=ooezL8cffNJGSc4TfNQp3u3WnDpkg8J3zFRczLuumceoYU5QYPs)

‚Äî


The entire process has been a learning experience for both of us, adapting and exploring the many possibilities to interact with each others‚Äô skills and ideas.

We really enjoyed building this project together and are excited as we invite you to take a dive into your very own urban playground!

Merci √† tous! Cheers!
  - Guillaume Cornet, Matthew Seremet

metadata.name: Corium #180
metadata.description:
The Corium is a roughly spherical mass (diameter ~1km), of currently unknown origins situated within the core region of the solar system's asteroid belt.
The body was discovered during a uranium extraction mission undertaken by ET Resources at the behest of Station 733-H (Mars colony) leadership, when ionising radiation levels detected by deployed surface craft exceeded equipment and personnel tolerance levels by many orders of magnitude.

While ETR crew were quick to respond to local abort orders (27 minutes from initial readings to fleet reorientation); Station 733-H made the determination that radiation exposure levels were already far in excess of anything that could be reasonably mitigated upon the ETR fleet's return.
The ETR fleet was ordered to jettison fuel reserves under Section 9 of the Space Corporations Act (Mars) approximately 90 minutes after the readings were initially reported. It is understood that all deployed personnel accessed their barbiturate rations within the following 24 hours.

The fleet itself remains in position some ~3000kms from The Corium, with plans to relocate the vessels still underway (albeit a low priority).


STATION 733-H OBSERVATION REPORT SUMMARY (14.1.1)

To date, remote analysis suggests that the body is compositionally similar to corium deposits observed following terrestrial nuclear disasters, consisting of a range of solidified radioactive compounds as well as a number of currently unidentified metal alloys. More in-depth analysis has been impossible to date due to the rapid physical decay of personnel and equipment as their proximity to samples reach a critical threshold.

All samples have so far been extruded from the surface of The Corium via laser, and maneuvered into orbit around Mars at the edge of it's sphere of influence (at a distance of no less than 50,000kms from Station 733-H), via projectile barrage and gas envelopment.

The surface of The Corium itself is littered with an array of clearly engineered forms; radial and rectangular patterns, deep crevasses, mazes and grids with only a select few areas resembling the pools of lava observed where Corium has formed terrestrially (it is unclear whether these deposits have formed since the surface was initially engineered).

The accompanying files are LIDAR renders of the extracted samples in proximity to Station 733-H and are marked for dissemination to terrestrial research teams on Mars. Study of The Corium remains the sole priority of Station 733-H research personnel, as any risks presented to the solar system or its inhabitants are currently not well understood.

--------------------------------------

The piece will render from the top right and might take ~5-10 seconds to begin.

Append "&print=true" to the live render URL for a hi-res output.

metadata.name: Flume #294
metadata.description:
Flume are infinitely flowing digital bodies of water.
The flow of Flumes can range from slow and gentle, creating small ripples and eddies, to fast and turbulent, carving its way through the inner workings of your computer screen. 
The color, clarity, and viscosity of the water can also vary.

This is the culmination of my collection Flume, an exploration into On-Chain art on Ethereum, https://etherscan.io/address/0x1fa23513825f952afca07a603ac3f312ebee4ca9

These pieces were all created in p5js.

- Andrew
